'''Antoine Selorm Semenyo''' (born 7 January 2000) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[winger (association football)|winger]] or [[wide midfielder]] for {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. Born in England, he plays for the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].

==Club career==
Semenyo had unsuccessful trials for London clubs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c5ygxx422eno|title=Antoine Semenyo: Bournemouth and Ghana forward motivated by trial rejections|date=4 November 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> At the age of 15, he was rejected by [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] after an eight-week trial. He initially decided to give up on becoming a professional footballer before [[Dave Hockaday]] convinced him to join his youth academy program at [[South Gloucestershire and Stroud College]].<ref name=sgscol>{{cite web |url=https://www.sgscol.ac.uk/news/CitysignSGSstudentAntoineSemenyo |title=City sign SGS student Antoine Semenyo |publisher=South Gloucestershire and Stroud College |accessdate=24 November 2022 }}</ref> Semenyo's development saw [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], Crystal Palace and [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] show interest in signing him.<ref name=sundayleague>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11743/13084394/antoine-semenyo-how-bournemouth-forward-went-from-sunday-league-to-premier-league-after-academy-rejection|title=Antoine Semenyo: How Bournemouth forward went from Sunday League to Premier League after academy rejection|date=1 March 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Prior to signing for Bristol City's academy in September 2017,<ref name=sgscol/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/semenyo-signed-up-from-sgs/|title=Semenyo signed up from SGS|date=20 September 2017|access-date=17 May 2026|website=Bristol City F.C.}}</ref> Semenyo had a brief spell at [[Hellenic Football League|Hellenic League]] side [[Highworth Town F.C.|Highworth Town]], playing the final 13 minutes of an [[FA Cup]] preliminary round tie against [[Marlow F.C.|Marlow]] on 20 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fulltime.thefa.com/displayFixture.html?id=17321693|title=Highworth Town 2–3 Marlow|access-date=17 May 2026|website=Full-Time FA}}</ref>

===Bristol City===
====Early appearances and loans====
Semenyo signed his first professional contract in January 2018 and joined [[Bath City F.C.|Bath City]] on a short-term loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/semenyo-goes-pro-and-heads-to-bath/|title=Semenyo goes pro and heads to Bath|date=19 January 2018|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Bristol City F.C.}}</ref> He scored six goals from 16 appearances for the [[National League South]] club before returning to Bristol City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wiltshiresportsacademy.co.uk/antoine-semenyo-achieves-world-cup-debut-10-5m-transfer|title=Antoine Semenyo achieves World Cup debut & £10.5M Transfer|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Wiltshire Sports Academy|date=5 September 2022 }}</ref> He made his Bristol City debut on the final day of the [[2017–18 Bristol City F.C. season|2017–18]] season coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Lloyd Kelly]] in the 3–2 loss to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]].<ref name="BBC Football">{{cite web |title=Bristol City 2–3 Sheffield United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43938863|work=BBC Football|date=6 May 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>

On 18 July 2018, Semenyo joined [[EFL League Two]] club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44874548 |title=Newport County sign Semenyo on loan from Bristol City |work=BBC Sport |date=18 July 2018 |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> He made his Newport debut in a 3–0 defeat against [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on 4 August 2018 as a second-half substitute<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44989421 |title=Mansfield Town 3–0 Newport County |work=BBC Sport |date=4 August 2018 |accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref> and scored his first goal for the club in a 4–1 [[2018–19 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] first round win over [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45092718|title=Carabao Cup: Amond double helps Newport hammer Cambridge 4–1|date=14 August 2018|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> At Newport, he began to play on the wing rather than his original position of striker.<ref name=sundayleague/> On 6 January 2019, he played the full 90 minutes as Newport knocked [[Premier League]] club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] out of the [[2018–19 FA Cup|FA Cup]] in the third round with a 2–1 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46713172|title=Newport County 2–1 Leicester in FA Cup third round|date=6 January 2019|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He also played the entirety of the 1–1 draw away at [[EFL Championship]] side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on 26 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/34651/11618281/middlesbrough-1-1-newport-matthew-dolan-leaves-it-late-to-earn-fa-cup-replay|title=Middlesbrough 1–1 Newport: Matthew Dolan leaves it late to earn FA Cup replay|date=26 January 2019|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> The following day, he was recalled by Bristol city after making 32 appearances in all competitions for the Welsh club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47024019 |title=Bristol City recall Antoine Semenyo from Newport County loan |work=BBC Sport |date=28 January 2019 |accessdate=28 January 2019 }}</ref>

Upon his return to Bristol City he was allocated the shirt number 18 and named as a substitute for the [[2018–19 EFL Championship|EFL Championship]] match away to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 9 February 2019. On 2 March, he appeared as a 53rd minute substitute for [[Callum O'Dowda]] in 1–1 draw with [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] and, seven days later, he made his first start for the club in a 1–0 home loss to [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/scout-report-antoine-semenyos-first-2629561|title=Scout report: Antoine Semenyo's first Bristol City start minute-by-minute|date=10 March 2019|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Bristol Live}}</ref> On 27 April 2019, Semenyo controversially received his first career red card against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] for a challenge on [[Tom Huddlestone]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47994358|title=Bristol City 0–2 Derby County: Lawrence and Bogle boost Rams' play-off hopes|date=27 April 2019|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> In June 2019, he signed a new four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48756475|title=Antoine Semenyo: Bristol City forward signs new four-year deal|date=25 June 2019|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>

After making eleven appearances for Bristol City, in the first half of the [[2019–20 Bristol City F.C. season|2019–20 season]], Semenyo was linked with a loan move to [[Sunderland]], [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] and a return to Newport County.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 January 2020 |title=Doncaster Rovers leading race to sign Sunderland January target Antoine Semenyo this month |url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/latest-sunderland-afc-news/doncaster-rovers-leading-race-to-sign-sunderland-january-target-antoine-semenyo-this-month-1353919 |access-date=20 February 2026 |website=Sunderland Echo |language=en}}</ref> On 31 January 2020, Semenyo joined [[EFL League One]] club Sunderland on loan for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/football/sunderland-afc/phil-parkinson-and-antoine-semenyo-react-youngster-joins-sunderland-and-goes-straight-squad-portsmouth-clash-1382156 |title=Phil Parkinson and Antoine Semenyo react as youngster joins Sunderland and goes straight into squad for Portsmouth clash |last=Smith |first=Phil |work=[[Sunderland Echo]] |date=31 January 2020 |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> He made seven appearances for Sunderland without scoring, making his only start in his final appearance at [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] on 10 March 2020. After the season was curtailed by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], he returned to Bristol City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shieldsgazette.com/sport/football/newcastle-united/newcastle-united-eye-ps50m-move-for-0-goal-ex-sunderland-winger-as-liverpool-plot-major-move-4865357|title=Newcastle United 'eye' £50m move for 0-goal ex-Sunderland winger as Liverpool 'plot' major move|date=17 November 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=The Shields Gazette}}</ref>

====First team breakthrough====
Semenyo began the [[2020–21 Bristol City F.C. season|2020–21]] by scoring his first goal for Bristol City in an [[EFL Cup]] first round tie against [[Exeter City]] on 5 September 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53955628|title=Bristol City 2–0 Exeter |publisher=BBC|date=5 September 2020 |accessdate=5 September 2020}}</ref> Eleven days later, he assisted goals for [[Chris Martin (footballer, born 1988)|Chris Martin]] and [[Kasey Palmer]], before scoring himself in a 4–0 win over [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] in the second round of the same competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54067071|title=Carabao Cup: Bristol City beat Northampton 4–0 to set up Aston Villa tie|date=16 September 2020|access-date=26 April 2025|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

During November 2020, he recorded assists in three consecutive [[EFL Championship]] matches against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]. He ended the season having played fifty competitive games, scoring five and assisting seven goals.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/what-is-the-current-situation-with-antoine-semenyo-at-bristol-city-we-take-a-look/|title=What is the current situation with Antoine Semenyo at Bristol City? We take a look|website=Football League World|first=Ned|last=Holmes|date=22 July 2021|access-date=9 October 2021}}</ref> He was named Bristol City's Young Player of the Year on 10 May 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/players-of-the-year-revealed/|title=Players of the year revealed|date=10 May 2021|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Bristol City F.C.}}</ref>

During the [[2021–22 Bristol City F.C. season|2021–22 season]], Semenyo registered eight goals and twelve assists in 32 games across all competitions.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/story-telling/11095/12651420/championship-tyrese-campbell-daryl-dike-among-25-of-the-most-exciting-talents-under-the-age-of-25|title=Championship: 25 under 25|work=Sky Sports }}</ref> He won the [[EFL Championship Player of the Month]] award for January 2022 after scoring three goals and getting three assists.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bcfc.co.uk/news/viva-semenyo-player-of-the-month/#:~:text=Antoine%20Semenyo%20has%20been%20voted,Rangers%20attacking%20midfielder%20Chris%20Willock. | title=🏆 Viva Semenyo – Player of the Month | date=11 February 2022 }}</ref>

Semenyo began the [[2022–23 Bristol City F.C. season|2022–23 season]] by scoring in a 3–1 [[2022–23 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] first round win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] on 24 August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62571846|title=Wycombe Wanderers 1–3 Bristol City: Kadji debut goal helps Robins progress in Carabao Cup|date=24 August 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He followed this up by scoring in his first two [[EFL Championship]] appearances of the season, against [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on 27 August and Huddersfield Town on 31 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12686217/bristol-city-2-0-huddersfield-nahki-wells-and-antoine-semenyo-steer-robins-to-victory|title=Bristol City 2–0 Huddersfield: Nahki Wells and Antoine Semenyo steer Robins to victory|date=31 August 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

During January 2023, he scored in three consecutive league matches against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12775541/coventry-1-1-bristol-city-antoine-semenyo-earns-point-for-robins|title=Coventry 1–1 Bristol City: Antoine Semenyo earns point for Robins|date=1 January 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64194816|title=Bristol City 4–2 Birmingham City: Mark Sykes scores twice as Robins beat Blues|date=14 January 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12791722/bristol-city-1-1-blackburn-rovers-antoine-semenyo-earns-point-for-robins|title=Bristol City 1–1 Blackburn Rovers: Antoine Semenyo earns point for Robins|date=21 January 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> as well as an [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]] third round tie against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64143538|title=FA Cup: Bristol City 1–1 Swansea City – Semenyo earns Bristol City a replay|date=8 January 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> This form saw reported interest from [[Premier League]] clubs [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and Crystal Palace, as well as two rejected offers from [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4127494/2023/01/26/bournemouth-transfer-antoine-semenyo/|title=Bournemouth agree deal for Antoine Semenyo after Bristol City accept third bid for forward|date=26 January 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=The Athletic}}</ref>
[[File:Alex Scott and Antoine Semenyo 27122025 (1).jpg|thumb|Semenyo playing for Bournemouth in 2025]]

===Bournemouth===
On 27 January 2023, Semenyo completed a transfer to Bournemouth worth £10&nbsp;million on a four-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64432637|title=Antoine Semenyo: Bournemouth sign Ghana forward from Bristol City|website=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2023}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in 1–0 [[2022–23 Premier League|Premier League]] loss at [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 4 February<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64436136|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1–0 Bournemouth: Kaoru Mitoma strikes late to earn victory|date=4 February 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and scored his first goal on 30 April 2023 in a 4–1 home win over [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fisher |first=Ben |date=30 April 2023 |title=Leeds woes deepen as Jefferson Lerma takes Bournemouth away from danger |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/apr/30/bournemouth-leeds-premier-league-match-report |access-date=30 April 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On 19 August 2023, Bournemouth's first away match of the [[2023–24 Premier League]] season, Semenyo gave the team a 1–0 lead over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[Anfield]] to register his second goal for the club. On 28 October, he scored in Bournemouth's first league win of the season and first under [[Andoni Iraola]] as they beat [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] 2–1 in matchday 10 of the Premier League. He ended his first full Premier League season with eight goals and two assists from 33 appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13107552/bournemouth-top-scorers-2023-24-dominic-solanke-clear-of-antoine-semenyo-and-justin-kluivert|title=Bournemouth top scorers 2023/24: Dominic Solanke, Antoine Semenyo and Justin Kluivert top goals chart|access-date=26 April 2024|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

On 8 July 2024, he signed a new contract with the club until 2029.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2024/july/08/semenyo-signs-news-contract/ |title=Semenyo sings new contract |publisher=AFC Bournemouth |date=8 July 2024 }}</ref> Semenyo began the [[2024–25 AFC Bournemouth season|2024–25 season]] by scoring an 86th-minute equaliser in a 1–1 draw with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 17 August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy8437kll7vt|title=Nottingham Forest 1–1 AFC Bournemouth: Late Antoine Semenyo strike earns draw|date=17 August 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Two weeks later he scored Bournemouth's first goal of a 3–2 comeback win over [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4213040|title=Everton 2–3 Bournemouth: A timeline of this season's incredible match|date=4 January 2025|access-date=26 April 2025|publisher=Premier League}}</ref> On 2 November 2024, he scored in Bournemouth's 2–1 win over Premier League champions [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at [[Dean Court]], ending City's eleven-month unbeaten run in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cwygp95enwrt|title=Bournemouth seal historic win against Man City|date=2 November 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His fifth goal of the season came in a 3–0 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]] on 22 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cwy3590ynxyt|title=Man Utd lose 3–0 at home to Bournemouth yet again|date=22 December 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 25 January 2025, he scored the fifth goal of Bournemouth's 5–0 win over Nottingham Forest, extending the club's unbeaten run in the Premier League to eleven matches.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cj48518eyzwt |title=Bournemouth 5–0 Nottingham Forest: Dango Outtara scores hat-trick as Cherries extend record run |date=25 January 2025 |access-date=26 April 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 14 April, Semenyo scored his tenth goal of the season to give Bournemouth a 1–0 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and end their run of six matches without a Premier League win. His goal came after 53 seconds of the match, making it Bournemouth's third-fastest Premier League goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4282491 |title=AFC Bournemouth beat Fulham to end six-match winless run |date=15 April 2025 |access-date=26 April 2025 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> On 25 May, Semenyo scored both goals in a 2–0 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] to end the season with a personal best eleven [[2024–25 Premier League|Premier League]] goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/god-is-working-behind-me-antoine-semenyo-after-surpassing-goal-contribution-at-bournemouth |title="God is working behind me" – Antoine Semenyo after surpassing goal contribution at Bournemouth |publisher=GhanaSoccernet |date=5 June 2025 }}</ref>

On 1 July 2025, Semenyo signed a contract extension at Bournemouth until 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Semenyo signs contract extension at Bournemouth until 2030 - MyJoyOnline |url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/semenyo-signs-contract-extension-at-bournemouth-until-2030/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |website=myjoyonline.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 15 August, Semenyo scored two goals away against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the opening match of the [[2025–26 Premier League]] season. His goals came in the 64th and 76th minutes to tie the match at 2–2 after Bournemouth had trailed 2–0 to the league champions, however, the match ended in a 4–2 defeat with Liverpool scoring two late goals.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=15 August 2025 |title=Liverpool struck twice late on as they opened the defence of their Premier League title with a dramatic victory over Bournemouth on an emotional night at Anfield. |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/ce833z5j7yzt |access-date=7 January 2026 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> He continued his strong start to the season with goals against Brighton and Hove Albion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/26806/13428721/bournemouth-2-1-brighton-controversial-antoine-semenyo-penalty-hands-dominant-cherries-victory|title=Bournemouth 2-1 Brighton: Controversial Antoine Semenyo penalty hands dominant Cherries victory|date=13 September 2025|access-date=1 March 2026|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> and Leeds United<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-antoine-semenyo-bournemouth-premier-league-elland-road-5336915|title=Antoine Semenyo makes Leeds United admission after Bournemouth draw with Whites praise and problem in plan|date=28 September 2025|access-date=1 March 2026|website=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> in September, before scoring two goals and assisting [[Justin Kluivert]] in a 3–1 win over Fulham on 3 October, taking him to six goals from the opening seven Premier League matches.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Begley |first=Emlyn |date=3 October 2025 |title=Antoine Semenyo scored twice as Bournemouth came from behind to beat Fulham in stormy conditions and move up to second in the Premier League table. |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cwylxyvq4jpt |access-date=7 January 2026 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>

After going seven matches without scoring, Semenyo scored in a 4–4 draw with Manchester United on 15 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c4g6jvj3d75t|title=Manchester United 4-4 Bournemouth: Hosts lose lead three times in Premier League classic|date=15 December 2025|access-date=1 March 2026|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He followed this up with goals against Burnley<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6907248/2025/12/21/antoine-semenyo-bournemouth-big-six-analysis/|title=Analysis: Antoine Semenyo and the qualities that make Bournemouth’s talisman an elite player|date=21 December 2025|access-date=1 March 2026|website=New York Times}}</ref> and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in Bournemouth's next two matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/antoine-semenyo-brentford-bournemouth-manchester-city-bees-b2890989.html|title=Kevin Schade hat-trick helps Brentford to convincing win over Bournemouth|date=27 December 2025|access-date=1 March 2026|website=The Independent}}</ref>

On 7 January 2026, having been strongly linked with a move to Manchester City in the January [[transfer window]], Semenyo scored in his final game for Bournemouth; a last-minute winner in a 3–2 win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[Vitality Stadium]], ending the Cherries' eleven-match run without a win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ce8e91ygd92t |title=Semenyo late stunner helps Bournemouth sink Spurs|last=Rajan|first=Adwaidh|date=7 January 2026|access-date=9 January  2026|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
On 9 January 2026, Manchester City announced the signing of Semenyo on a five-and-a-half-year contract for a reported fee of £64 million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Antoine Semenyo joins Man City: Bournemouth forward signs in £64m transfer to take City spending over £425m in 12 months |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13491956/antoine-semenyo-joins-man-city-bournemouth-forward-signs-in-lb64m-transfer-to-take-city-spending-over-lb425m-in-12-months |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47537480/man-city-transfer-antoine-semenyo-bournemouth-64-million-premier-league |title=Man City sign Antoine Semenyo from Bournemouth in £64M deal |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=www.espn.com}}</ref> He made an immediate impact on his debut the following day, scoring once and providing an assist in a 10–1 FA Cup victory over Exeter City.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/762497 |title=Antoine Semenyo scores as Man City thrash Exeter 10-1 |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=www.espn.com}}</ref> Three days later, he opened the scoring in a 2–0 away win against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the first leg of the EFL Cup semi-final, helping City progress 5–1 on aggregate to reach the [[2026 EFL Cup final]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/401842433 |title=Semenyo scores again as Man City get semifinal edge over Newcastle |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=www.espn.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=EFL |date=4 February 2026 |title=Manchester City Beat Newcastle 5-1 on Aggregate to Reach Carabao Cup Final |url=https://efl.com/news/2026/february/04/ruthless-man-city-sweep-past-newcastle-to-reach-carabao-cup-final/ |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=EFL |language=en}}</ref>

On 24 January, Semenyo scored his first Premier League goal for City in a 2–0 victory over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=read |first=Foot Africa·1 min |date=24 January 2026 |title=Antoine Semenyo: First Premier League goal with Manchester City |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/articles/antoine-semenyo-first-premier-league-180000774.html |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> His impressive run of form throughout February earned him the Premier League Player of the Month award.<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2026 |title=Semenyo wins his first EA SPORTS Player of the Month award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4611431/semenyo-wins-his-first-ea-sports-player-of-the-month-award |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=www.premierleague.com |language=en}}</ref> On 22 March, he featured in Manchester City's 2–0 victory over Arsenal in the EFL Cup final, securing his first trophy with the club.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/401859837 |title=Manchester City win Carabao Cup as Nico O'Reilly double silences Arsenal |access-date=16 May 2026 |website=www.espn.com}}</ref>

On 16 May, Semenyo scored the decisive goal in the [[2026 FA Cup final]] against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], producing a backheel finish to seal a 1–0 victory and deliver the trophy to Manchester City.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Smyth |first=Rob |date=16 May 2026 |title=Manchester City win FA Cup final as Semenyo magic sinks Chelsea 1-0 – live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2026/may/16/chelsea-v-manchester-city-fa-cup-final-live |access-date=16 May 2026 |work=the Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in England, Semenyo is of Ghanaian descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ghanasportsonline.com/2019/08/performance-of-ghanaian-players-abroad-yartey-sparkles-ache-strikes-as-antwi-hits-brace-as-20-players-score-23-goals-abroad/|title=Performance of Ghanaian Players Abroad: Yartey sparkles, Ache strikes as Antwi hits brace as 20 players score 23 goals abroad – Ghana Sports Online|date=12 August 2019|access-date=7 May 2020|archive-date=16 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221016173519/https://ghanasportsonline.com/2019/08/performance-of-ghanaian-players-abroad-yartey-sparkles-ache-strikes-as-antwi-hits-brace-as-20-players-score-23-goals-abroad/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Silas |first=Don |date=4 September 2024 |title='My mother is from France' - Antoine on why he snubbed France, England |url=https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-antoine-on-why-he-snubbed-england-france/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=5 April 2025 |newspaper=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post]]|language=en-US |archive-date=10 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240910113312/https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-olise-on-why-he-snubbed-england-france/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Semenyo was called up to the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]] on 26 May 2022<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37628818/ghana-call-bristol-city-striker-antoine-semenyo|title=Ghana call up Bristol City striker Antoine Semenyo|date=26 May 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> and made his debut for the ''Black Stars'' in a 3–0 [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] win over [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] on 1 June.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/06/01/africa/africa-cup-of-nations-qualification/ghana/madagascar/3783008/ | title=Ghana vs. Madagascar – 1 June 2022 – Soccerway }}</ref>

On 14 November 2022, Semenyo was included in Ghana's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/africa/63576436| title=World Cup 2022: Jojo Wollacott ruled out of Ghana squad after finger injury| work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first international goal in the team's final warm-up match for the tournament, a 2–0 win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 17 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/articles/cnd513yy5g3o|title=How Ghana beat Switzerland 2–0 for international friendly|language=pcm|date=17 November 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC News Pidgin}}</ref> At the tournament finals, he made two substitute appearances in the group matches against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63657472|title=World Cup 2022: Portugal 3–2 Ghana – Ronaldo, Felix and Leao score|date=24 November 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63752147|title=World Cup 2022: Ghana 0–2 Uruguay – De Arrascaeta scores twice|date=2 December 2022|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

Semenyo's first competitive goal for Ghana came in the sixth minute of stoppage time in an [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group E|Africa Cup of Nations qualifier]] against [[Angola national football team|Angola]] on 23 March 2023, giving the ''Black Stars'' a 1–0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65058091|title=Ghana 1–0 Angola: Antoine Semenyo scores as Chris Hughton wins first game in charge|date=23 March 2023|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In January 2024, he was named in Ghana's squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67285720|title=Afcon 2023: Squads for tournament including Ghana, Nigeria and Egypt|date=12 January 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He started all three group matches at the tournament as Ghana were eliminated with two draws and a loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://supersport.com/football/africa-cup-of-nations/news/578493df-dfa6-4266-917c-d3f6cda3ee66/black-stars-dumped-out-of-afcon-following-mambas-stalemate|title=Black Stars dumped out of Afcon following Mambas stalemate|date=23 January 2024|access-date=26 April 2025|website=SuperSport}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Semenyo's father, Larry, is a former footballer, having played as a midfielder for [[Okwawu United S.C.|Okwawu United]] in the [[Ghana Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://footy-ghana.com/2022/05/photos-antoine-semenyo-models-in-ghana-kit-to-mark-debut-black-stars-call-up/ |title=PHOTOS: Antoine Semenyo models in Ghana kit to mark debut Black Stars call-up |publisher=Footy Ghana |date=26 May 2022 |accessdate=24 November 2022 |archive-date=24 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221124182139/https://footy-ghana.com/2022/05/photos-antoine-semenyo-models-in-ghana-kit-to-mark-debut-black-stars-call-up/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Antoine also holds French citizenship from his mother.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Silas |first=Don |date=2024-09-04 |title='My mother is from France' - Antoine on why he snubbed France, England |url=https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-antoine-on-why-he-snubbed-england-france/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=2025-04-05 |newspaper=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post]]|language=en-US |archive-date=10 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240910113312/https://dailypost.ng/2024/09/04/my-mother-is-from-france-olise-on-why-he-snubbed-england-france/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Semenyo's younger brother [[Jai Semenyo|Jai]] is also a professional footballer, currently at [[Championnat National 1]] side [[FC Lorient B]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristolworld.com/sport/football/bristol-city/pride-ghana-jai-and-the-rise-of-a-bristol-city-star-antoine-semenyos-father-and-ex-coach-discuss-3601188|title=Pride, Ghana, Jai and the rise of a Bristol City star: Interview with Antoine Semenyo's father|date=27 May 2022 |publisher=bristolworld.com}}</ref>

On 18 November 2025, Semenyo proposed to his long-time girlfriend, Jordeen Buckley.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bamfo |first=Andrews Sefa |date=18 November 2025 |title=Ghana forward Antoine Semenyo proposes to his girlfriend - Kickoffghana.com |url=https://kickoffghana.com/ghana-forward-antoine-semenyo-proposes-to-his-girlfriend/ |access-date=18 November 2025 |language=en-US}}</ref>

